anks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German:","from Middle High German <i>rieme</i> ‘band, strap’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a (leather) strap maker, or a nickname for a wearer of such items.","topographic name from the same word as 1 in the sense ‘narrow strip of land’, or a habitational name from Riem near Munich. Compare   Reams  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Reams","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): of Norman origin, a habitational name from Rames in Seine-Maritime (France). This surname is rare in Britain. Compare   Rheams  .","Americanized form of German   Riehm  ."]},{"name":"Ream","meanings":["Perhaps an Americanized form of German   Riehm  ,   Rehm  , or <b>Röhm</b> (see   Roehm  ).","English: perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>reaume</i>, <i>reame</i> ‘realm, dominion’, although the context for the adoption of this word as a surname is unclear."]}]},{"name":"Nicholeus","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Nichols  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nichols","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]}]},{"name":"\"Nicholas\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholeus \"Nicholas\" Riehm was born in 1432, in Germany, his father, Everhard Riehm, was 23 and his mother, Fräulein Andreas Riehm, was 21. He married Fräulein Nicholeus Riehm in 1457, in Leimen, Rhein-Neckar-Kreis, Baden-Württemberg, Germany. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1490, in Baden, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1432–1490":"1432–1490","1437–Female":"1437–Surnud","1465–1509":"1465–1509","1409–1477":"1409–1477","1411–Female":"1411–Surnud","1437":"1437","1457":"1457","1477":"1477","1411":"1411","1432":"1432","1465":"1465","1431":"1431","1509":"1509","1409":"1409","1490":"1490","Leimen, Heidelberg, Baden-Württemberg, Germany":"Leimen, Rhein-Neckar-Kreis, Baden-Württemberg, Saksamaa","Leiman, Germany":"Saksamaa","Leimen, Heidelberg, Baden, Germany":"Leimen, Amt Heidelberg, Baden","Leimen, Bezirksamt Heidelberg, Kreis Heidelberg, Großherzogtum Baden, Deutsches Reich